

1. What is the purpose of the static folder in Flask?


Static folder serves unchanging files like CSS, JavaScript, images directly to browser without processing. Flask automatically serves files from /static/ path.

Contains:

static/

├── css/

│   └── style.css

├── js/

│   └── main.js

└── images/

&nbsp;   └── logo.png







2. How do you link CSS from the static folder?



Use url\_for('static', filename='...') in HTML templates:



xml

<!DOCTYPE html>

<html>

<head>

&nbsp;   <link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ url\_for('static', filename='css/style.css') }}">

</head>

<body>

&nbsp;   <h1>My Flask App</h1>

</body>

</html>



URL becomes: http://localhost:5000/static/css/style.css







3. Difference between static and templates folder?



| Static                    | Templates                    |

| ------------------------- | ---------------------------- |

| Raw files (CSS/JS/images) | Processed HTML (Jinja2)      |

| Direct browser serving    | Flask renders with variables |

| /static/css/style.css     | /home.html                   |

| No Flask processing       | {{ variable }} → values      |



Static = Give file as-is ✅

Templates = Fill in blanks 🔄







4. Can Flask serve images from the static folder?



YES - automatic:



In HTML:



xml

<img src="{{ url\_for('static', filename='images/logo.png') }}" alt="Logo">



In Python route:



python

return f'<img src="/static/images/photo.jpg">'



Folder structure:



static/images/

├── logo.png

├── hero.jpg

└── avatar.png







5. What is `url\_for()` used for?



	Generates correct URLs dynamically - handles changes if static folder moves or app URL changes.



| Hardcoded ❌           | url\_for() ✅                                 |

| --------------------- | ------------------------------------------- |

| /static/css/style.css | url\_for('static', filename='css/style.css') |

| Breaks if URL changes | Always works                                |

| Manual updates        | Auto-adjusts                                |



Examples:



xml

<link href="{{ url\_for('static', filename='css/main.css') }}" rel="stylesheet">

<script src="{{ url\_for('static', filename='js/app.js') }}"></script>

<img src="{{ url\_for('static', filename='img/logo.png') }}">



Static folder + url\_for = Professional styling guaranteed! 🎨✨

